 model:`, `Action model:`, `Recent findings:`, `Open questions:`, `Plan:`, and `Cross-level notes:`.\nWhen calling `python`, emit exactly the tool-call format shown elsewhere in this prompt for this model. Use only that format; do not add markdown fences, prose wrappers, or alternate tool-call syntax. Do not quote or place tool-call markup inside explanatory text; when you decide to call the tool, emit the tool call itself.\nIf you use MOUSE, include integer row and col arguments.\nEFFICIENCY BUDGET \u2014 your score on each level is (baseline_actions / your_actions)^2, so every wasted action costs you quadratically.\nLevel 2: you have used 8 of about 81 target actions so far.", "kind": "tool", "inContext": true}, {"label": "THINKING", "content": "Very interesting! When I clicked the purple object, ALL the green cells came back! The state reverted to having 5 green cells at (15,13), (15,19), (15,31), (15,43), and (51,43). The purple object acted as an \"undo\" or \"reset\" button.\nSo the purple object resets the board to the initial state. That means I need to find a better strategy. In level 1, I had to click each green cell individually to move them. But maybe I can batch the moves more efficiently.\nLet me think about what happened in level 1:\n- 5 green cells, needed to click each one (show target) then click the target (move) = 2 actions per green cell = 10 actions total\n- But the level was completed with fewer actions because some greens merged\nFor level 2, I have 5 green cells. The key insight is that when I click a green cell, it shows g diamonds around the target. When I click the g diamond, the green moves there. I need to figure out the correct sequence.\nLet me try a more efficient approach: click green cells and immediately move them to their targets in batch.", "kind": "reasoning", "inContext": false}, {"label": "TOOL CALL: python", "content": "<tool_call>\n<function=python>\n<parameter=code>\n# Current state has 5 green cells. Let me click each one